    <center><table class="itemDisplayTable">
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Title:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Toxicity of Volatile Organic Compounds (VOC’s) on Indian Major Carp - Catla Catla (Hamilton)</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Authors:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Nirmala.G.N</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Keywords:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Toxicity of Volatile Organic Compounds<br />Indian Major</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Issue Date:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Mar-2014 </td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Publisher:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">SRM University</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Series/Report no.:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">T0139</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Abstract:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Indian major carp, Catla catla were exposed to progressive concentrations of
dichloromethane (DCM), monochlorobenzene (MCB) and 1, 2-dichlorobenzene (DCB)
by static renewal method according to guidelines of OECD. The acute toxicity tests were
conducted using 10 fishes for different concentrations and control group. The results
were subjected to Probit analysis to determine the 96 hour LC50 values. The 96 hour
LC50 values of DCM, MCB and DCB for Catla catla were 19.75 mg/L, 5.8 mg/L and
1.4 mg/L respectively. In addition, behavioral changes at each concentration were
observed for the individual fish. The fishes were exposed to two sub lethal
concentrations of 1/2 and 1/8 of 96 hour LC50value of DCM, MCB and DCB for a
period of up to 28 days.
It was observed that increase in exposure time from 0, 1, 7, 14, 21 and 28 days,
the total erythrocyte (RBC), hemoglobin (Hb), packed cell volume (PCV) and platelet
(PLT) values decreased but leucocytes (WBC), mean corpuscular volume (MCV), mean
corpuscular hemoglobin concentration (MCHC) and mean corpuscular hemoglobin
(MCH) values increased. It was observed that depression in packed cell volume and
hemoglobin values were coupled with decreased and deformed erythrocytes with
obvious signs of anemia. The exposure to sublethal doses of DCM, MCB and DCB for
1, 7, 14, 21 and 28 days exposure period caused significant (P &lt;0.05) time and dose
dependent alterations in glutamine, lactate, free amino acids, pyruvate and total protein
level compared to the control values. The enzyme activities of acetylcholinesterase, alkaline phosphatases and protease in gills, liver, muscles and brain tissues of fish were
also varied compared to the control fish. Thus, DCM, MCB and DCB had potent
piscicidal activity against Catla catla and adversely affect their behavioral patterns,
shifting to aerobic pathway of fish respiration and inhibiting energy production by
suppressing ATP synthesis.
The oxidative damage and anti-oxidant properties were studied in Catla catla
exposed to DCM, MCB and DCB in sub-acute toxicity tests as pollution biomarkers.
The increased activities of anti-oxidant enzymes like catalase (CAT), superoxide
dismutase (SOD) and glutathione S-transferase (GST) after 28 days exposures to VOC’s
were observed due to more prominent stress suggesting the activation of physiological
mechanism to scavenge the ROS produced. The decreased values of reduced glutathione
(GSH) on 28 days exposures to DCM, MCB and DCB indicated the functioning of this
antioxidant enzyme either to scavenge oxyradical or to act in combination with other
enzymes.
In general, a concentration dependent response was observed in gills and blood
with maximum DNA damage at the highest concentration of DCM, MCB and DCB. The
genotoxic studies were carried out using Single Cell Gel Electrophoresis for in vivo
assessment of DNA damage caused by the sub-lethal concentrations of DCM, MCB and
DCB to fish blood and gills. The trend in the DNA damage scores of the blood samples
were similar to those that was observed in the gills, and a significant increase of DNA
damage as noted at 24 hours and at all doses at 28 days. The results indicated that DCM,MCB and DCB caused genotoxicity in the form of strand breaks in the DNA of fish as
evidenced by the alkaline comet assay.
The histological observations showed pathological lesions of the gills included
infiltration of secondary lamellae, inter-lamellae hyper plastic lesion, edema, congestion
of the blood vessels, epithelial thickening and lifting, and necrosis of various degrees are
concentration dependent. The histological changes in the gills and liver included
hepatocyte degeneration, nuclear pycnosis, cellular swelling, and congestion of blood
vessels. There was a marked difference in these changes between the two selected
concentrations of DCM, MCB and DCB and the intensity of histological changes were
influenced by the extent of exposure period. Our results using alkaline comet assay
indicated that this assay can be used as a valuable biomarker for the evaluation of water
pollution.</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">URI:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue"><a href="http://hdl.handle.net/123456789/15797">http://hdl.handle.net/123456789/15797</a></td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Appears in Collections:</td><td class="metadataFieldValue"><a href="/dspace/handle/123456789/6855">Ph.D - Thesis  </a><br/></td></tr>
</table></center><br/>
